{"parse":{"title":"Doerner Institute","pageid":27087913,"revid":854580671,"text":{"*":"<div class=\"mw-parser-output\"><p><b>Doerner Institute</b> was founded in 1937 <a href=\"/wiki/Munich\" title=\"Munich\">Munich</a> as a <i>State Testing and Research Institute for Colour Technology</i> (in German <i>Staatliche Pr\u00fcf- und Forschungsanstalt f\u00fcr Farbentechnik)</i>.\n</p>\n<div id=\"toc\" class=\"toc\"><input type=\"checkbox\" role=\"button\" id=\"toctogglecheckbox\" class=\"toctogglecheckbox\" style=\"display:none\" /><div class=\"toctitle\" lang=\"en\" dir=\"ltr\"><h2>Contents</h2><span class=\"toctogglespan\"><label class=\"toctogglelabel\" for=\"toctogglecheckbox\"></label></span></div>\n<ul>\n<li class=\"toclevel-1 tocsection-1\"><a href=\"#The_founding_of_the_Institute\"><span class=\"tocnumber\">1</span> <span class=\"toctext\">The founding of the Institute</span></a></li>\n<li class=\"toclevel-1 tocsection-2\"><a href=\"#Current_Activities\"><span class=\"tocnumber\">2</span> <span class=\"toctext\">Current Activities</span></a></li>\n<li class=\"toclevel-1 tocsection-3\"><a href=\"#References\"><span class=\"tocnumber\">3</span> <span class=\"toctext\">References</span></a></li>\n<li class=\"toclevel-1 tocsection-4\"><a href=\"#Institute&#39;s_Website\"><span class=\"tocnumber\">4</span> <span class=\"toctext\">Institute's Website</span></a></li>\n</ul>\n</div>\n\n<h2><span class=\"mw-headline\" id=\"The_founding_of_the_Institute\">The founding of the Institute</span><span class=\"mw-editsection\"><span class=\"mw-editsection-bracket\">[</span><a href=\"/w/index.php?title=Doerner_Institute&amp;action=edit&amp;section=1\" title=\"Edit section: The founding of the Institute\">edit</a><span class=\"mw-editsection-bracket\">]</span></span></h2>\n<p>The Institute takes its name from <a href=\"/wiki/Max_Doerner_(Artist)\" class=\"mw-redirect\" title=\"Max Doerner (Artist)\">Max Doerner</a>, an artist and Munich Art Academy professor. His book, <i>The Materials of the Artist and their Use in Painting</i> published in 1921 had established Doerner's reputation and his argument which is quoted in Phillip Ball's \"Bright Earth\" provided the inspiration for the institute. That argument was that <i>the artist cannot be expected to be chemist; he would only become victim of a dilettantism more harmful than beneficial....[Yet] the laws which govern the materials of the artist are the same for all artists, to whatever school they belong. Whoever wishes to employ his materials correctly and to the best advantage must know these laws and follow them, otherwise sooner or later he will pay dearly for his mistakes.... Craftsmanship must again be made the solid foundation of art.</i><sup id=\"cite_ref-1\" class=\"reference\"><a href=\"#cite_note-1\">&#91;1&#93;</a></sup><sup id=\"cite_ref-di_2-0\" class=\"reference\"><a href=\"#cite_note-di-2\">&#91;2&#93;</a></sup>\n</p>\n<h2><span class=\"mw-headline\" id=\"Current_Activities\">Current Activities</span><span class=\"mw-editsection\"><span class=\"mw-editsection-bracket\">[</span><a href=\"/w/index.php?title=Doerner_Institute&amp;action=edit&amp;section=2\" title=\"Edit section: Current Activities\">edit</a><span class=\"mw-editsection-bracket\">]</span></span></h2>\n<p>Since 1977 the Institute has been home to the conservation department of the <a href=\"/wiki/Bayerische_Staatsgem%C3%A4ldesammlungen\" class=\"mw-redirect\" title=\"Bayerische Staatsgem\u00e4ldesammlungen\">Bayerische Staatsgem\u00e4ldesammlungen</a> as well as its \"own\" science department. Other activity undertaken at the Institute includes\n</p>\n<ul><li>research into historical painting techniques and materials</li>\n<li>development of scientific methods applied to objects of art</li>\n<li>museum design or the renovation of historic buildings used as museums.<sup id=\"cite_ref-di_2-1\" class=\"reference\"><a href=\"#cite_note-di-2\">&#91;2&#93;</a></sup></li></ul>\n<h2><span class=\"mw-headline\" id=\"References\">References</span><span class=\"mw-editsection\"><span class=\"mw-editsection-bracket\">[</span><a href=\"/w/index.php?title=Doerner_Institute&amp;action=edit&amp;section=3\" title=\"Edit section: References\">edit</a><span class=\"mw-editsection-bracket\">]</span></span></h2>\n<div class=\"reflist\" style=\"list-style-type: decimal;\">\n<div class=\"mw-references-wrap\"><ol class=\"references\">\n<li id=\"cite_note-1\"><span class=\"mw-cite-backlink\"><b><a href=\"#cite_ref-1\">^</a></b></span> <span class=\"reference-text\">Ball, Philip (2001) Bright Earth: The Invention of Colour, Vintage</span>\n</li>\n<li id=\"cite_note-di-2\"><span class=\"mw-cite-backlink\">^ <a href=\"#cite_ref-di_2-0\"><sup><i><b>a</b></i></sup></a> <a href=\"#cite_ref-di_2-1\"><sup><i><b>b</b></i></sup></a></span> <span class=\"reference-text\"><a rel=\"nofollow\" class=\"external free\" href=\"http://www.doernerinstitut.de/en/geschichte/geschichte_1.html\">http://www.doernerinstitut.de/en/geschichte/geschichte_1.html</a></span>\n</li>\n</ol></div></div>\n<h2><span id=\"Institute.27s_Website\"></span><span class=\"mw-headline\" id=\"Institute's_Website\">Institute's Website</span><span class=\"mw-editsection\"><span class=\"mw-editsection-bracket\">[</span><a href=\"/w/index.php?title=Doerner_Institute&amp;action=edit&amp;section=4\" title=\"Edit section: Institute&#039;s Website\">edit</a><span class=\"mw-editsection-bracket\">]</span></span></h2>\n<ul><li><a rel=\"nofollow\" class=\"external free\" href=\"http://www.doernerinstitut.de/\">http://www.doernerinstitut.de/</a></li></ul>\n\n<!-- \nNewPP limit report\nParsed by mw1326\nCached time: 20180903182410\nCache expiry: 1900800\nDynamic content: false\nCPU time usage: 0.032 seconds\nReal time usage: 0.040 seconds\nPreprocessor visited node count: 106/1000000\nPreprocessor generated node count: 0/1500000\nPost\u2010expand include size: 335/2097152 bytes\nTemplate argument size: 81/2097152 bytes\nHighest expansion depth: 7/40\nExpen